[{"id":"VR781550","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR781548.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following correctly justifies why the motion can be called simple harmonic motion?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR781550_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A physical pendulum is constructed of a small block of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 m\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2 m\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mn>2</mn> <mi>m</mi> </math></span></span> attached to the end of a uniform rod of length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"l\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"l\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>ℓ</mo></math></span></span> and mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"m\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math></span></span>. The rotational inertia of the rod about its end is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"one third , times m , script l  squared\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"one third , times m , script l  squared\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mpadded><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msup><mo>ℓ</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mpadded></mstyle></math></span></span>. The rod is pulled back a small angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"theta\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span> and released at time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 0\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"t equals 0\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span>, as shown. The rod is vertical at time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t sub v\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"t sub v\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>t</mi><mtext>v</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a pendulum which consists of a rod of mass m attached to a block of mass 2 m. The rod is attached to the ceiling by a pivot, and makes an angle of theta with the vertical. The distance from the pivot to the center of the block is l.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR781548.g02.svg\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The torque is directly proportional to the sine of the angle that the pendulum makes with the vertical, regardless of how large the angle is.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The pendulum is released at a small angle, so the torque is directly proportional to the angle that the pendulum makes with the vertical.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The torque is directly proportional to how far the end of the pendulum is from its equilibrium position, regardless of how far from equilibrium it is.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The torque is directly proportional to the length of the pendulum.</p>"],"answer":1}]